<TEXT>
the heads of amherst college and the 
university of massachusetts have joined forces to condemn an annual 
snowball fight that nearly blinded a student in one eye this winter 
the two school leaders released a statement thursday blasting the 
dec 14 fight as amherst college prepared a lawsuit against its 
neighbor umass for building damages and medical costs incurred by 
the injured student gary e gonya 19 of toledo ohio 
the freshman student had to undergo emergency surgery to save 
an eye in light of this incident it has become clear to us that we 
can no longer tolerate the continuation of this tradition 
amherst president peter r pouncey and umass chancellor joseph d 
duffey said in the statement 
pouncey estimated damage to the school at more than 10000 in 
the last several years the two school leaders promised to educate 
our students about the dangers of this event and plan other 
measures to deter students from participating 
amherst spokeswoman terry allen said it was unclear what further 
measures the schools will take she said police have been unable to 
identify gonyas assailants from videotapes of the snowball fight 
the fights usually take place on the first significant snowfall 
of the year university students march to the amherst campus a mile 
away and engage in battle 
amherst college will seek a preliminary injunction to allow 
campus and town police to arrest anyone found instigating a snowball 
fight at the school said school spokesman douglas wilson 
the complaint against umass is expected to be filed with 
hampshire superior court in the next few days according to wilson 
duffey and pouncey contended that the violence has escalated as 
students have begun packing snowballs with rocks that have broken 
several dormitory windows gonya who may have been hit with a 
snowcovered rock spent five days in hospitals in northampton and 
boston doctors say his vision is blurry but he will regain sight 
in a few months 
in 1987 umass paid more than 3000 to amherst college for 
damages from that years snowball fight the college claims umass 
still owes 1788 from last years bombardment 
i dont think this university as an institution is liable for 
the behavior of its students once they leave the campus duffey 
has said 
</TEXT>
