<TEXT>
newspaper headlines show a vastly different japan 
from the nation that george bush fought five decades ago in world 
war ii 
japan launches scientific satellite a routine matter 
exosd is japans 12th spacecraft to go into orbit to study the 
earth 
japanese airline announces multibilliondollar airliner 
purchase also routine boeings biggest customer is japan air 
lines and wednesdays order by its competitor all nippon airways 
could make ana the biggest buyer of boeings new 747400s and hack 
7 billion off the us trade deficit 
funeral diplomacy in full swing as world leaders arrive 
not routine japan buries emperor hirohito on friday the first 
imperial funeral in 62 years despite memories of aggression 
committed in hirohitos name in world war ii his funeral has 
brought dignitaries from more than 160 countries to tokyo 
university of tokyo political science professor seizaburo sato 
said there were two reasons for so many countries to come one is 
the increasing interdependence of the countries throughout the 
world and the second is the increasing importance of japan in the 
world community 
japan is rich it is exerting international influence through 
financial power while its military strength is held in check by a 
postwar constitution that rejects force as a way of dealing with 
international disputes 
in many ways japan is about as up to date as you can get its 
industrial prowess has made its automakers into global operators who 
produce more motor vehicles than us competitors in high 
technology the japanese are at the forefront of superconductivity 
research and computer developments 
the robust economy is propelled by the renowned diligence and 
managerial skill of the japanese at the governments urging the 
economy is being restructured to depend more on domestic consumption 
than on the export drives that led to trade imbalances and friction 
with other countries 
one problem is politics which is widely held to have been 
corrupted by the tide of cash that has accompanied japans rise to 
economic superpower 
a headline in thursdays mainichi shimbun questioning of 
political figures looms the story said that prosecutors 
investigating suspected bribery are on the verge of deciding whether 
to question 17 politicians about ethically dubious share 
transactions that benefitted them or their aides 
among those politicians is prime minister noboru takeshita the 
chairman of the committee organizing hirohitos funeral and playing 
host to the presidents kings prime ministers and other foreign 
officials now in tokyo also on the list are takeshitas 
predecessor yasuhiro nakasone and other leaders of the liberal 
democratic party 
all have denied any wrongdoing but some japanese media are 
speculating that takeshita will not last long despite his announced 
intention to clean up political ethics starting right away 
still looming are those prosecutors who arrested eight 
businessmen and bureaucrats in the last two weeks for questioning on 
suspicion of bribery or securities law violations but havent 
touched the politicians yet 
the conservative party has governed since world war ii with the 
exception of 10 months of socialist cabinets in 194748 it holds 
fat majorities in both houses of the diet or parliament 297 of 
512 seats in the house of representatives and 143 of 252 in the 
upper house of councillors 
in july however elections will be held for half the upperhouse 
seats and the ruling party is worried a setback would probably 
send takeshita to the back benches of the diet and the recruit 
scandal has tainted so many leaders of his party that its hard to 
guess who would succeed him 
another of thursdays headlines ldps man quits race for 
governor over recruit funds recruit co is the conglomerate at 
the center of the stocktrading scandal threatening the ruling 
party and it has become anathema to have received its donations 
the news story says that takeshita persuaded his candidate kazuo 
aichi to withdraw from the miyagi prefecture gubernatorial race 
because aichi had received 60000 in donations from recruit since 
1975 
the conservatives long grasp on power has both stultified 
politics and encouraged corruption analysts say its also widely 
held that the conservatives probusiness policies helped make japan 
the peaceful economic giant it has become after being laid waste in 
the war 
this conundrum of money politics linked with economic strength is 
making the japanese especially thoughtful as they close a long 
chapter of history in burying their emperor of 62 years 
a headline from thursday evenings television news prosecutors 
question former ntt head ntt or nippon telegraph and telephone 
co is the most valuable company in the world in terms of stock 
market capitalization its former chairman hisashi shinto had a 
reputation as an exponent of clean business and politics until he 
resigned last year in disgrace after it was shown he had profited in 
the recruit scandals shady stock transactions 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
larry thorson is asia news editor for the 
associated press 
