negotiations with the soviets to reduce longrange nuclear 
weapons were to resume last week the talks have been postponed 
indefinitely although nato and the warsaw pact will open separate 
negotiations on nonnuclear forces in vienna on march 7 
the reagan administration was aiming at a 50 percent reduction in 
strategic nuclear missiles bombers and submarines the two main 
obstacles to completing a treaty were the us strategic defense 
initiative and finding ways to verify compliance with the accord 
policymakers in the bush administration may be less committed to 
the search for a spacebased defense against ballistic missiles 
that could point to a compromise with the soviets who are 
determined to slow down the star wars program 
on the other hand brent scowcroft the assistant to the 
president for national security affairs might push for development 
of a new mobile missile that could complicate the verification 
problem as well as require a recalculation of some tentative 
weapons ceilings set during the reagan administration 
and completing the start treaty could be delayed even further 
</TEXT>
