<TEXT>
a longpredicted downturn in military 
recruiting has begun with army recruiters missing their quotas for 
the first time this decade the pentagon says 
the other three military services managed to hit their enlistment 
quotas for the first quarter of fiscal 1989 but also are showing 
signs of distress the pentagon said thursday 
the downturn has been predicted for more than a year primarily 
because of the strong economy and a dwindling pool of 18yearolds 
but we need to act now to head off future recruiting 
problems said grant s green jr the assistant defense secretary 
for force management and personnel 
the first step is to work with congress on military pay and to 
restore the value of recruiting incentives advertising resources 
and education benefits he said otherwise we could begin the 
chain of events that led to the serious military manpower problems 
of the last decade 
the latest manpower report covers the period from last oct 1 to 
dec 31 during those three months the four services had a combined 
quota of 61900 people 
the services signed up 61700 or just 200 shy of their goal 
but breaking the statistics down by individual service the army 
fell short of its goal of 24143 by 475 men and women the first 
such decline since 1980 
the navy managed to exceed its quarterly goal of 18900 by 
signing up 19200 men and women but it did so by calling up 
earlier than expected volunteers who had joined the delayed entry 
program to put off their military service by a few months 
the army and navy also had to increase the percentage of 
category 4 volunteers or low scorers on the military entrance 
test that they accepted the report shows the army had to accept 
almost 11 percent of its recruits from category 4 more than double 
the 4 percent level maintained for the past three years 
the marine corps matched its recruiting goal during the quarter 
by bringing in 7100 men and women and the air force also matched 
its objective of 11800 
but the marine corps and air force have reported they are 
working harder to meet their recruiting objectives green said 
while the department still considers this recruiting 
performance to be good environmental factors cannot be ignored 
green said thursday 
unemployment is at a 14year low the youth population will 
continue to decline through fiscal 1996 and budgetary pressures 
remain a concern 
according to census bureau projections the pool of 18yearolds 
in the united states has been declining for some years and wont 
begin increasing again until at least 1996 
