<TEXT>
a military jury on friday 
convicted a us navy captain of dereliction of duty for failing to 
help a boatload of vietnamese refugees who later resorted to 
cannibalism to survive then spared him a harsh sentence 
capt alexander balian a highly decorated vietnam war veteran 
was sentenced to a reprimand he could have been jailed for 90 days 
and ordered to forfeit twothirds of his pay for three months 
the jury acquitted balian 48 of the more serious charge of 
ordering one refugee shaken off ropes as he tried to climb aboard 
the warship 
this court martial sentences you to be reprimanded said the 
jury foreman capt william fox after deliberating the sentence for 
about a half hour under military law court martial convictions are 
automatically reviewed 
the jury of six navy captains deliberated nearly six hours 
thursday and friday before returning a verdict 
balian of los angeles had been on trial since feb 10 
he was stripped of his command of the amphibious landing ship uss 
dubuque after being accused of failing to render adequate assistance 
to more than 80 vietnamese boat people when the dubuque encountered 
them june 9 in the south china sea 230 miles north of the 
philippine island of palawan 
un officials said 31 of the vietnamese died after encountering 
the dubuque survivors said they resorted to cannibalism to survive 
before filipino fishermen rescued them on june 27 
the jury found balian guilty of dereliction of duty for failing 
to conduct an adequate inspection of the refugee boat determine 
whether their sail was adequate conduct appropriate medical 
examinations of visibly dehydrated refugees provide necessary 
navigational equipment provide adequate food and clothing to the 
naked and take refugees aboard or see to it that they were taken 
aboard or assisted by a navy supply ship in the area 
the jury found balian innocent of charges that he ordered the 
dubuques crew to shake off a refugee who tried to climb aboard the 
warship using the vessels monkeylines 
on feb 16 balian was acquitted of a third charge failing to 
render assistance to a vietnamese who drowned 
the prosecution contended balian abandoned the refugees in his 
rush to resume his voyage to the persian gulf 
providing humanitarian assistance is a mission of the us 
navy the prosecutor lt cmdr raymond carlson said during 
closing arguments it was not capt balians mission it was an 
interruption to his mission 
carlson said the vietnamese left their homeland may 22 with the 
aim of escaping to freedom they planned a fourday voyage to 
malaysia but were stranded when their engine broke down after three 
days at sea he said 
food ran out and about 20 vietnamese had already died when they 
encountered the dubuque he said 
carlson said balian pressed his executive officer lt cmdr 
stanley halter to rush through an inspection of the refugee boat 
balian testified he did not pick up the refugees because he did 
not realize how desperate their situation was balian also testified 
that he believed the vessel was seaworthy based on reports from 
halter 
only a fool would think this vessel could effectively sail 
anywhere said carlson holding a photo of the boat jammed with 
emaciated vietnamese 
only a fool can think these people are not in a 
lifeendangering situation only a fool could really think food and 
water were all that was needed in this situation 
in his summation defense lawyer dan donato urged the jury to 
consider that balian was honestly mistaken about conditions on 
the boat 
it was a tragedy of errors donato said if the skipper had 
learned there were dead bodies if he had known people were 
sick he would have taken different actions if he had known there 
was an inoperable engine he would have taken a different action 
donato also said balian was under pressure from his commanders to 
reach the persian gulf on schedule the dubuque took part in us 
security operations in the gulf during the final weeks of the 
iraniraq war 
capt balian was told to be there donato said he was 
told dont be late 
