<TEXT>
hirohito the emperorgod made mortal by a 
disastrous war was honored friday at a traditionsteeped state 
funeral attended by the largest number of world leaders gathered 
together in modern times 
an explosion on a roadside embankment marred the day spilling 
dirt and debris on a highway shortly before the motorcade carrying 
the emperors body and the imperial family was to pass police said 
the motorcade bound on a chilly rainy day for the imperial 
burial site west of tokyo passed the area where the blast occurred 
without incident 
police said they suspected radicals who oppose the imperial 
system were responsible several such groups had vowed to disrupt 
the funeral for which japans police mounted their biggest security 
operation ever 
at the funeral service 51 blackrobed bearers carried atop a 
oneton bier the body of the emperor who died in january at age 87 
after a reign of 62 years that spanned japans rise to militarism 
its defeat in world war ii and its ascent as a world economic power 
the people will remember him forever said his son and the 
new emperor akihito in a eulogy before leaders of 163 nations 
including president bush 
a deepvoiced male chorus sang a solemn song a poem was read and 
members of the imperial family went individually before the coffin 
and bowed slowly 
after the eulogies bush and his wife barbara stepped to the 
front of the hall paused and made a slight bow before the coffin 
the capital a sprawling metropolis of 12 million people came to 
a standstill as 32000 police were deployed to protect the 
dignitaries 
police said the highway blast occurred about 15 minutes after the 
imperial motorcade left the funeral site in westcentral tokyo it 
was not immediately clear how far away the motorcade was at the time 
of the blast 
there was no immediate claim of responsibility 
early in the day a black hearse carrying the emperors 
lacedraped coffin drove at 6 mph through central tokyo along a 
fourmile route from the moated imperial palace to the funeral site 
at shinjuku imperial garden 
police said about 210000 people lined the streets some people 
cried as the motorcade passed and others held their palms together 
in prayer 
members of the royal family carried umbrellas in the streaming 
rain and wind 
