<TEXT>
president bush is meeting the four men who guide 
modern china and its communist party during his twoday visit 
starting saturday 
two of them top leader deng xiaoping and president yang 
shangkun are octogenarians representatives of the old guard of 
preliberation revolutionaries 
the other two communist party general secretary zhao ziyang and 
premier li peng are younger leaders concerned less with ideology 
and more with guiding chinas 1 billion people toward a 21st century 
of economic prosperity 
deng xiaoping 84 is the architect of chinas bold experiments 
in economic reform he holds no official position except chairman of 
the central military commission but no one questions deng is the 
man in charge 
a former red army comissar who helped lead the communists to 
victory in 1949 deng is a survivor of mao tsetungs political wars 
who has spent the past decade undoing much of maos ideological 
heritage 
deng was purged during the leftist 196676 cultural revolution as 
a capitalist roader but battled his way back after maos death 
in 1976 by the end of the 1970s he was chinas undisputed leader 
deng rejected maos concept of the primacy of class struggle and 
made economic development his top priority in the past decade he 
has abolished the commune revived the family farm and encouraged 
private enterprise 
he has also promoted the stillunfinished tasks of freeing 
factory managers from bureaucratic interference creating a price 
system based on market forces rather than government dictum and 
forging a welltrained mobile labor force 
deng has tolerated slow expansion of intellectual and artistic 
freedoms and has encouraged increased contacts with the outside 
world particularly the west in 1979 he toured the united states to 
mark the establishment of uschina relations but politically his 
instincts are conservative several times he has cracked down on 
political dissent when he felt it threatened the supremacy of the 
party or the nations stability 
yang shangkun 81 became chinas fourth president or head of 
state in april last year 
yang like deng was born in sichuan province and played an 
active role in red army campaigns of the 1930s and 1940s purged 
during the cultural revolution the career military man returned to 
public office in the late 1970s and in 1982 was appointed permanent 
vice chairman of the central military commission 
as senior military officer on the commission he backed dengs 
1985 decision to end the wartime footing of the army and cut 1 
million troops from the force of more than 4 million 
the post of president is largely ceremonial and yang is not 
thought to be an initiator of policy but he does have a voice 
because of his close ties to deng and his seat on the 17member 
party politburo chinas top decisionmaking body 
zhao ziyang 69 for the past decade has been chinas leading 
advocate of speed and boldness in initiating economic reforms 
he made his reputation as party secretary and governor of sichuan 
in the late 1970s when he led the nation in highly successful 
experiments in restoring family farming 
in 1980 deng brought him to beijing and he was quickly named 
premier a post he held until 1987 
zhao became acting general secretary of the communist party in 
january 1987 following the ouster of fellow reformist hu yaobang 
who was blamed for prodemocracy student unrest he officially took 
over chinas most powerful post the following november 
zhao known for his immaculately tailored western suits his 
cosmopolitan manner and his love for golf has been widely regarded 
as the man most likely to succeed deng as chinas senior leader 
however there have also been persistent reports publicly denied 
by chinese officials that zhaos stature has suffered during 
chinas recent economic woes 
zhao reportedly has been criticized for pushing decentralization 
and price reforms too quickly contributing to the outofcontrol 
pace of industrial growth and inflation of more than 20 percent 
zhao now has joined the more cautious premier li peng in backing 
a twoyear slowdown in reform while the government tries to restore 
eocnomic growth to a manageable level 
li 60 in april completes his first full year as premier or 
head of government an electrical engineer who studied in the soviet 
union in the 1950s li represents the new breed of technocrats now 
filling the ranks of the chinese government 
li has tried with only limited sucess to shake off the 
impression that he is a conservative who opposes zhaos efforts to 
move quickly in introducing marketoriented reforms 
he consistently supports the reforms but with the qualifier that 
they not be implemented at a speed that will threaten economic or 
social stability 
li appeared to have gained the upper hand last september when the 
government announced its twoyear hold on reforms and said central 
authorities would reimpose controls in such areas as banking and 
foreign trade 
li a native of sichuan was cared for by the late premier chou 
enlai after his father was killed by the nationalists when li was 3 
years old he joined the party at age 17 
after returning from six years in the soviet union in 1954 he 
held a number of important engineering posts and was named minister 
of power industry in 1979 he was appointed vice premier in 1983 and 
served as education minister from 1985 
li along with zhao is a member of the fivemember politburo 
standing committee the pinnacle of power within the party 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

