<TEXT>
emperor hirohito once considered a god 
was laid to rest friday in a hillside forest with ancient ritual 
the music of pipes drum and gong and a pair of white shoes to 
carry him to home to heaven 
he was buried in a white silk kimono but a western suit and tie 
his customary dress were entombed with him 
also buried with him were a microscope he used in 50 years of 
research as a respected marine biologist and a list of rankings of 
wrestlers in the traditional sport of sumo which hirohito followed 
avidly the newspaper yomiuri reported palace officials would not 
confirm the report 
a heavily guarded procession carried hirohitos coffin to the 
mausoleum 30 miles west of tokyo inside the gates of the musashi 
imperial cemetery his son and successor emperor akihito led the 
imperial family in burial ceremonies modeled on ancient shinto rites 
a 21gun salute echoed through the green forest to herald the 
processions arrival court musicians playing pipes flutes drum 
and gong led the funeral party up the gray graveled lane 
approaching the mausoleum the hearse followed a group of 
attendants in black or green robes carrying shields pikes banners 
of yellow and white and two of the evergreen sakaki trees held 
sacred by the shinto religion 
an official carried the white shoes 
akihito followed by empress michiko led the funeral party to a 
graveside funeral hall of golden japanese cypress a gray curtain 
was drawn and the coffin was placed on a cart inside the hall 
members of the family withdrew to a nearby guest house where 
they spent three hours and the coffin was pulled 100 feet up a 
slope to the tomb 
the rites were steeped in the ritual of shinto the indigenous 
religion that preceded the introduction of buddhism to japan and 
still coexists with it in both faiths care is taken to show 
respect to the dead and ensure peaceful rest 
funeral ceremonies for hirohito who died jan 7 at age 87 
lasted more than 13 hours those for his father emperor taisho in 
1927 lasted 1 days and mourners dared not even look at the oxdrawn 
hearse 
modern technology was used this time to speed the process a 
motorized hearse instead of an ox cart for the 30mile trip from 
tokyo to the cemetery floodlights to supplement the traditional 
torches and three trucks loaded with premixed concrete to seal the 
coffin in the tomb 
offerings by court ritualists of clothing and 16 types of food 
including cakes of pounded rice oranges rice wine and melons 
ended the entombment well after dark 
akihito offered a sacred sakaki branch and made his final long 
deep bow michiko also offering a sakaki branch and other members 
of the imperial family then paid their last respects followed by 
officials 
hirohitos moundlike stone mausoleum which will be completed in 
one year sits in a quiet forest of towering cypress trees not far 
from the graves of his parents emperor taisho and empress teimei 
