<DOCNO> AP890224-0167 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal bank regulators in a report to 
congress released friday rejected charges that their policies 
discourage banks from forgiving part of the huge debt owed by third 
world countries 
current regulatory policy and accounting policies have not 
prevented banks that were otherwise inclined to do so from 
participating in a wide range of negotiated debt reduction 
transactions with borrowing countries three regulatory agencies 
said in a report to the senate banking committee 
critics of current policy say banks are discouraged from 
realistically recognizing losses on third world debt they say banks 
should be permitted to spread the effects of recognizing losses over 
several years currently they must reduce their profit by the full 
amount of any addition to loss reserves 
however the federal reserve board office of the comptroller of 
the currency and the federal deposit insurance corp said accounting 
standards are designed to present a true picture of banks financial 
condition adding accounting policies are not intended to 
encourage or discourage any actions that management considers to be 
in the best interest of the institution 
they cited world bank estimates showing that 20 billion in 
developing country debt has been eliminated in the past two years 
the three agencies also said that banks exposure to developing 
country debt had improved considerably since the crisis first 
emerged in 1982 but was still large for the nations 10 biggest 
banks 
at the end of september the 10 largest banks were on the hook to 
developing countries for loans representing 95 percent of the banks 
capital and loss reserves 
and the report endorsed the continuation of the socalled baker 
plan which rejects taxpayer contributions toward solving the 
problem and encourages casebycase negotiations for additional 
lending rather than any coordinated plan of debt forgiveness 
the approach is named after secretary of state james a baker 
iii who developed while serving as ronald reagans treasury 
secretary 
the bank regulatory agencies continue to believe the 
casebycase negotiated approach is the best method the report 
said 
president bush has said his administration will take a new look 
at the approach but has advocated no specific changes 
on another point the report said the secondary market for 
selling and swapping third world loans is a poor indicator of the 
loans true value many analysts say they are worried because the 
loans are now worth about 40 percent of their original value down 
from 60 percent in mid1987 the regulators said secondary market 
prices may reflect shortterm supply and demand rather than the 
longterm value of the loans 
the regulators report is the first installment toward meeting 
the requirements of a section of last years trade act a second 
report due by may 31 will examine the effects of third world 
lending on bank profits between 1977 and 1987 
the treasury department was supposed to deliver another report 
this week on new approaches for solving the debt crisis but was 
given a threeweek extension 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

