<TEXT>
a federal judge on friday dismissed 
racketeering charges against three men indicted last month in the 
pentagon procurement investigation defense attorneys said 
while the men two private consultants and a suspended navy 
procurement specialist are no longer accused of racketeering they 
face a number of other criminal charges stemming from the jan 7 
indictment including bribery and theft of government property 
us district judge richard williams issued his ruling from the 
bench and said he would file a written order next week according 
to gerard treanor a lawyer for william l parkin a defendant 
treanor said the judge agreed with the defense arguments that 
prosecutors had not presented enough evidence to satisfy 
racketeering charges against consultants parkin and fred h lackner 
and stuart e berlin a navy official who has been suspended without 
pay 
defense attorneys said a significant result of the dismissal was 
that the government would no longer be able to seize cash and other 
assets of the defendants under provisions of the racketeer 
influenced and corrupt organizations act 
the three men were charged with racketeering and conspiracy to 
commit racketeering as part of a 27count indictment returned by a 
federal grand jury 
the 86page indictment also included charges against teledyne 
electronics of newbury park calif a defense contractor that is a 
branch of teledyne inc of los angeles and three teledyne employees 
but neither teledyne electronics nor its employees were charged 
with racketeering which carries a penalty of 20 years in prison and 
a fine of 250000 the penalty for conspiracy to commit 
racketeering is five years in jail and a 250000 conviction on a 
racketeering charge can also result in forfeiture of any property 
garnered illegally 
attorneys said williams also dismissed some wire fraud counts 
against the defendants but refused to grant motions to drop other 
charges the trial is set to begin on march 27 
in the indictment the first in the governments 212 year 
investigation into the defense purchasing system prosecutors 
claimed that teledyne and three of its officers agreed to pay parkin 
160000 to assist them in obtaining a navy contract related to 
radar 
the indictment contended that parkin then paid lackner a 
californiabased consultant who in turn paid berlin to manipulate 
the contracting procedures so that teledyne was assured of receiving 
the contract 
the governments coasttocoast investigation of the 150million 
pentagon purchasing system codenamed operation ill wind 
centers of allegations that companies paid private consultants to 
illegally obtain information about lucrative contracts prosecutors 
based much of their information on telephone wire taps 
