<TEXT>
the federal aviation administration proposed a 
801000 fine against northwest airlines on friday for violations 
including the use of boeing jumbo jets on 8198 flights without a 
required engine bolt inspection 
the airline was also charged with making unauthorized repairs on 
two 747s and failure to comply with a dozen other faa rules and 
directives 
the airline has 15 days to respond to the civil penalty the 
proposed fine amounts to a settlement offer from the faa which will 
take effect if the airline does not object the faa said it first 
outlined the alleged violations in a feb 17 letter to northwest 
president john f horn 
william slattery northwest executive vice president for 
operations described the problems as primarily instances of 
inadequate record keeping and differences in interpretation 
slattery said none of the issues questions the safe operation of 
airliners belonging the minneapolisbased airline he said the 
airline had completed original required inspections but had not 
accomplished repetitive followup inspections 
he said discussion between the faa over the past year had reduced 
the number of alleged violations from 139 to a dozen and the airline 
would continue to discuss the remaining matters with federal 
authorities 
our objective is to ensure northwest is adhering to all federal 
aviation regulations slattery said noting that other faa fines 
against airlines had ranged from 252000 to 95 million 
one case in the latest proposed penalty involved northwest 
failing to comply with an faa airworthiness directive for 
inspecting engine pylon attach bolts on 24 boeing 747s while 
continuing to fly the planes the faa said 
although afterthefact checks did not disclose any defects in 
the bolts these 8198 flights constituted violations of safety 
regulations because the airline did not do the inspections in the 
specified time frame the faa said 
the unauthorized repairs were on flap panels and horizontal and 
vertical stabilizers on two 747s the agency said 
it said other allegations included improperly deferring 
maintenance and flight crew overscheduling 
the problems were discovered during a monthlong indepth faa 
inspection of the airline in january and february 1988 as part of a 
national safety inspection program the faa said it published a 
100page report on the inspections in march which included praise 
of northwest for conducting its own internal audit which led to 
several changes in company practices before the start of the faa 
inspection 
