<TEXT>
the talk of okinawa these days is about a gift 
a royal heir has made to the district where he lives in tokyo its 
angry talk 
okinawans are angered because they feel the heir has given away 
symbols of their golden age of independence long ago 
hiroshi sho the greatgrandson of okinawas last king has 
chosen to give the taito ward in tokyo his collection of more than 
1000 family heirlooms and the ownership of a royal tomb in shuri 
once the seat of okinawan royalty and now a neighborhood of naha 
the capital of okinawa prefecture 
the tomb called the tamaudun is a threeroom structure with 
limestone outer walls and sunbaked plazas of coral ground into a 
fine white sand generations of okinawan royalty are buried there 
local reaction to shos decision disclosed in december by a 
tokyo newspaper has often been colored by lingering friction 
between the majority yamato japanese a broad term referring to most 
of the inhabitants of japans main islands and the uchinanju or 
okinawans 
when i heard the news it felt like the yamato people had done 
it to us again said taxi driver tamotsu yonaha it has hurt our 
pride 
his shos wife is japanese so i guess it stands to reason 
said an old woman selling herbal tea at a market but it still 
belongs to us 
a special session of the prefectural assembly was convened in 
january and after two days of discussion the assembly called shos 
choice regrettable 
statements of protest were issued by business leaders civic 
organizations and even some of shos relatives several small groups 
have organized grassroots opposition 
however yoshin hirata assistant director of the prefectural 
education agencys culture division said tokyo and the japanese are 
not to blame he credited taito ward with trying to work out a 
compromise 
they dont want to have us glaring at them forever he said 
it seems that sho simply wanted his estate to be kept near 
home which for him is tokyo 
sho also has told the okinawan government that he believes the 
tokyo ward will make the collection more accessible to researchers 
from all over the world 
after being approached by sho the taito ward one of 23 
administrative subdivisions in tokyo agreed to establish a 
24million foundation to care for the objects and keep the 
collection in one place the ward has a population of about 177000 
though disappointing mr hiroshi sho believes that setting up 
the foundation with taito ward is the best solution and i would 
like to respect his view gov junji nishime of okinawa said in a 
statement 
the 70yearold sho who was born in tokyo refuses to meet with 
reporters 
letters to the editor of the okinawa times which has run dozens 
of reports on the issue have been strongly against the foundation 
according to senior editorial writer akiko yui 
he has lived in tokyo all his life and i think he has little 
affection for okinawa she said noting that shos parents are 
buried in taito ward 
what the okinawans are feeling is the irony that the descendant 
of their king is no longer an okinawan 
sho is the greatgrandson of okinawas last king tai sho who 
died in 1901 okinawa was unified into the chuzan kingdom during the 
15th century and in its heyday traded with china korea and 
southeast asia 
in 1609 the kingdom was invaded by warriors from southern japan 
and required to pay taxes the islands were incorporated into japan 
in 1879 ending the local monarchy members of the okinawan royal 
family were encouraged to move to tokyo and marry yamato japanese 
which most of them did many okinawans believe the royals were 
forced to assimilate into japanese culture 
okinawans have felt they were discriminated against over the 
years by the japanese during world war ii attempts were made to 
wipe out their five main dialects which are often incomprehensible 
to speakers of standard japanese 
many okinawans blamed the government in tokyo for the heavy 
fighting in 1945 on okinawa which was as close to japan proper as 
us forces reached before the japanese surrendered more than 
100000 civilians died in the battle which also claimed the lives 
of 110000 japanese soldiers and 12500 americans 
following postwar occupation by the united states okinawa was 
turned over to japanese administration in 1972 20 years after the 
occupation of japan had ended 
the japanese emperor gave okinawa to america said an 
okinawa times editorial after emperor hirohitos death jan 7 the 
descendant of okinawas emperor has for free given tokyos taito 
ward okinawas possessions 
we wont ask which crime is more serious but to the people of 
okinawa there is just a feeling of misery 
