<TEXT>
colombia will temporarily freeze oil 
exports to cooperate with opecs and independent producers efforts 
to stabilize world oil prices energy and mines minister oscar mejia 
vallejo said friday 
our decision is rather symbolic since we are not in a position 
to increase significantly our export levels which in turn 
represent only an insignificant portion of the world market he 
told reporters 
colombia is the second nonopec country to announce a change in 
exports since tuesdays meeting of independent producers in london 
mexico said earlier it would reduce exports by up to 5 percent 
in a statement released after the london meeting the group said 
several nations had agreed either to cut or to freeze exports in the 
second quarter to cooperate with the organization of petroleum 
exporting countries efforts to reduce output and increase world oil 
prices the group also said details of the agreement would be 
released later analysts speculated the cuts would total about 
200000 barrels a day 
opec established a new sixmonth quota that took effect jan 1 
under which it was to cut production to 185 million barrels about 
4 million barrels less than it was producing at the end of 1988 
although the cartel is said to be producing more than 19 million 
barrels prices have risen about 5 a barrel since the quota was 
announced last november 
colombia whose oil industry has experienced problems including 
guerrilla attacks on its pipelines has made it clear that it was 
not in the position to reduce exports 
colombia exports 180000 barrels out of a total 435000 barrels 
produced daily the south american country said it is working to 
expand domestic oil pipelines and increase its production capacity 
to 600000 barrels per day next year 
