<TEXT>
an increase in the federal reserves key lending 
rate drove bond prices lower and shortterm interest rates higher 
friday 
the feds antiinflation action pushed its discount rate the 
interest it charges on loans to member banks from 65 percent to 7 
percent its highest level in about three years 
the treasurys closely watched 30year bond tumbled about 
point or 375 for every 1000 in face value its yield which 
moves inversely to its price jumped to 918 percent from 914 
percent late thursday the highest level since september 
rates on shortterm government bonds came under the most pressure 
the short end got pretty well crushed right after the news of 
the discountrate hike said steven a wood an economist with 
bankamerica capital markets group in san francisco 
it was just confirmation that the fed really means business in 
terms of inflation it confirmed that the fed has clearly 
tightened he said 
a hike in the discount rate normally drives shortterm interest 
rates higher as some banks must borrow to meet reserve requirements 
the discount rate is now at its highest level since april 1986 
in the secondary market for treasury bonds prices of shortterm 
government issues fell point to 316 point intermediate 
maturities declined point to 932 point and longterm issues lost 
516 point according to figures provided by telerate inc a 
financial information service 
the movement of a point is equivalent to a change of 10 in the 
price of a bond with a 1000 face value 
the shearson lehman hutton daily treasury bond index which 
measures price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with 
maturities of a year or longer fell 215 to 111803 
in corporate trading industrials also retreated moodys 
